hina -- tIn and out of the local -- tWhat's wrong with global art? -- tglobal art history and transcultural studies -- tlooking for something -- tnomadic territories and times -- tDead parrot society -- tGeoaesthetic hierarchies: geography, geopolitics, global art, and coloniality -- tAfterword -- tNotes on the contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe "biennale culture" now determines much of the art world. Literature on the worldwide dissemination of art assumes nationalism and ethnic identity, but rarely analyzes it. At the same time there is extensive theorizing about globalization in political theory, cultural studies, postcolonial theory, political economy, sociology, and anthropology. Art and Globalization brings political and cultural theorists together with writers and historians concerned specifically with the visual arts in order to test the limits of the conceptualization of the global in art. Among the major writers on contemporary international art represented in this book are Rasheed Araeen, Joaquín Barriendos, Susan Buck-Morss, John Clark, Iftikhar Dadi, T. J. Demos, Néstor García Canclini, Charles Green, Suman Gupta, Harry Harootunian, Michael Ann Holly, Shigemi Inaga, Fredric Jameson, Caroline Jones, Thomas DaCosta Kaufmann, Anthony D. King, Partha Mitter, Keith Moxey, Saskia Sassen, Ming Tiampo, and C. J. W.-L. Wee. Art and Globalization is the first book in the Stone Art Theory Institutes Series. The five volumes, each on a different theoretical issue in contemporary art, build on conversations held in intensive, weeklong closed meetings. Each volume begins with edited and annotated transcripts of those meetings, followed by assessments written by a wide community of artists, scholars, historians, theorists, and critics. The result is a series of well-informed, contentious, open-ended dialogues about the most difficult theoretical and philosophical problems we face in rethinking the arts today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt and globalization. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAraeen, Rasheed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakoš, Ján, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarlow, Tani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarriendos, Joaquín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanclini, Néstor García, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDadi, Iftikhar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemos, T. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElkins, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElkins, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGabara, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGopnik, Blake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrzinic, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Suman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarzombek, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Caroline A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Alice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKing, Anthony D., econtributor.4ctb4htt